Patch Set 1:

Adding Paul as a reviewer. It looks like the patch is essentially reverting some changes from his earlier patch https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/32000 so let's get his feedback.

Background info for Paul....

Raja reported that when the extended tests are run, some of the VRRP tests always fail with errors like:

==============================================================================
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/opt/vpp_dev/vpp/test/test_vrrp.py", line 375, in test_vrrp4_backup_noadv
    pkts = [self.vrrp_adv_packet(prio=prio+10, src_ip=src_ip)]
  File "/opt/vpp_dev/vpp/test/test_vrrp.py", line 200, in vrrp_adv_packet
    dst_ip = self._adv_dest_ip
AttributeError: 'TestVRRP4' object has no attribute '_adv_dest_ip'
==============================================================================

This patch is intended to fix those errors.

Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

This is awesome!! Thanks a lot! 

Probably we'll need a few iterations on this patch as I get to understand how to run it. But before anything else, can we make paketdrill (extras/vcl-ldpreload/packetdrill-test/packetdrill) a git submodule, to avoid storing all of that code in our repo?

Patch Set 3:

A few more comments/questions after reading through the patch:
- packetdrill is GPL licensed so we really can't have the code in the vpp repo. Probably the best option at this point is to have a script that builds it after a git clone. If patching is needed either 1) fork, clone and patch 2) consider upstreaming fix/feature patches. 
- Is packetdrill.c needed because we're overriding some of the netdev functions or some other reason? Independent of that, why do we need to link it against ldp given that we're LD_PRELOADING the tests? Could we move the file into packedrill (either overwrite the exiting one or make it a plugin if that's possible) build and run as is with ldp?

Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

There is a reason for 2s

Patch Set 4:

> There is a reason for 2s

Is the reason documented somewhere, so we can decide whether it is still valid?

I see the very first public commit was already overriding the default value, in one case even to 1 second [0]. Not sure if that was bumped later or whether the script was removed.

The passing (1n-skx) device test job proves VPP is able to do its work in 1 second. There can be discussion about the two negative cases (blacklist), but similar whitelist test is passing, and I expect the performance to be similar.

I can add time tracking so we can see how fast VPP actually is (currently the command takes 1.7 seconds, but that includes virtualenv activation and similar).

This is a good point but probably needs a bit more investigation, i.e., I suspect we may not re-initializing some fields and we should. Is this a case of the caller providing a very large list of events or a side effect of the busy polling done by ldp (no eventfds)?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> This is a good point but probably needs a bit more investigation, i.e., I suspect we may not re-initializing some fields and we should. Is this a case of the caller providing a very large list of events or a side effect of the busy polling done by ldp (no eventfds)?

I checked implementation of epoll_wait in kernel code, and events also were not memset. In the case, I tested redis with eventfds, a large traffic with memtier_benchmark and making CPU usage up to 80%. I checked CPU usage with perf, memset in epoll_wait occupied 50% CPU usage.

> > > This is a good point but probably needs a bit more investigation, i.e., I suspect we may not re-initializing some fields and we should. Is this a case of the caller providing a very large list of events or a side effect of the busy polling done by ldp (no eventfds)?
> > 
> > I checked implementation of epoll_wait in kernel code, and events also were not memset. In the case, I tested redis with eventfds, a large traffic with memtier_benchmark and making CPU usage up to 80%. I checked CPU usage with perf, memset in epoll_wait occupied 50% CPU usage.
> 
> By the way, only avx2 is supported in my machine.

So this is a case of busy polling by ldp whereby most of the time is spent checking if there are any events and that memset is exercised, hence it becomes so heavy, right? It should be worth fixing the memset but we need to probably improve how events are initialized in vcl_epoll_wait_handle_mq to avoid CI failures. However the gains will not be that significant for blocking scenarios, i.e., when we epoll_wait the vcl worker's mq eventfd.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

From last discussion i will only accept epoch time in reviews in csit. I will start replacing monotonic everywhere

Patch Set 1:

My current rule is:
If singular value is exposed outside its current scope, it has to be epoch.
If only difference of two values (measured within the same scope) is exposed, the values have to be monotonic.
There are some gray areas, e.g. when start_traffic remembers a time and stop_traffic computes and exposes the difference, I prefer monotonic.

In past I also had a rule for variable name parts. "time" or "timestamp" for time.time(), "duration" or "timedelta" for time.monotonic() difference. But there is too much of legacy code to force one naming scheme.

What about this pattern?

  monotonic_start = time.monotonic()
  result = do_something()
  duration = time.monotonic() - monotonic_start
  export_result(result, timestamp=time.time(), duration=duration)

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

For this patch set, monotonic measurements are close enough to be considered the same scope, but the value should not be printed (only the difference). I will rework.
